Research static analysis techniques for detecting race conditions, thread safety violations, and concurrency anti-patterns across multiple programming languages. Cover the following language-specific models: Java's synchronized, volatile, and java.util.concurrent; Python's GIL limitations and its exceptions with ctypes, subprocesses, and C extensions; Go's goroutine and channel model with the race detector tool; Rust's ownership model and Send/Sync trait enforcement; and C++ with std::mutex and std::atomic. For static analysis specifically (not runtime detection), research the following tools and techniques: RacerD (Facebook's static race detector for Java and C++), ThreadSanitizer as a dynamic baseline for evaluating static tools, CHORD and its Datalog-based approach, and the concurrency analyses built into Infer. Document the precision and recall of static race detectors compared to dynamic detectors on benchmarks like the IBM Concurrency Benchmark or RaceBench. Research which race condition patterns are detectable with only file-level AST analysis (no cross-file dataflow) versus those that require interprocedural analysis. Cover double-checked locking, lock-before-read patterns, atomicity violations distinct from data races, and the TOCTOU (time-of-check-time-of-use) pattern. The practical goal is calibrating what a file-level static race condition scanner can and cannot reliably detect.
